  "author_association": "MEMBER",
  "active_lock_reason": null,
  "body": "As reported in #517, `TokenTimelock` uses `uint64` for its timestamp state variable.\r\n\r\nAs I explained elsewhere: `uint256` is the only integer size native to the EVM. For all other integer sizes, the Solidity compiler generates extra operations to e.g. truncate on overflow. Because of this, using uint64 doesn't really lead to smaller contracts or less gas costs.\r\n\r\nWe should be using `uint256` for consistency.",
